The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where increasing resource needs lead to plundering and war, and where growing production capacity over the last decades brings more pollution and global warming in its wake.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so on.
Von ihren Gegnern werden sie als „Ökonomen des Überflusses“ gesehen, die dem Markt vertrauen, der angeblich alle Probleme löst.
Aber statt Tatsachen und Geschichten herauszupicken, die in eine große Erzählung von Niedergang oder Fortschritt passen, sollten wir versuchen, alle Bereiche der menschlichen Existenz zu vergleichen, um zu sehen, ob die Welt tatsächlich besser oder schlechter geworden ist.
Genau dies habe ich gemeinsam mit 21 weltweit führenden Ökonomen dadurch zu erreichen versucht, dass wir eine Wertungsliste der letzten 150 Jahre entwickelten.
In zehn Bereichen – darunter Gesundheit, Bildung, Krieg, Geschlechterverhältnis, Luftverschmutzung, Klimaveränderung und Biodiversität – haben die Ökonomen für jedes Jahr von 1900 bis 2013 dieselbe Frage beantwortet: Wie hoch waren die relativen Kosten dieses Problems in jedem einzelnen Jahr, einschließlich Prognosen bis 2050?
Anhand klassischer ökonomischer Bewertungen aller Faktoren von Todesopfern, Gesundheitsproblemen und Analphabetentum über die Veränderungen in Feuchtgebieten bis hin zu höherem Hurrikan-Risiko durch globale Erwärmung zeigen die Ökonomen die Kosten jedes einzelnen Problems auf.
To assess the magnitude of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available to solve it.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 have been surprisingly mixed.
Let's consider gender inequality.
Essentially, we excluded almost half of the world population from production at that time.
1900 were only 15% of the world's workforce female.
What are the losses that arise from this small percentage?
Even if we take into account the higher costs of women's education and that someone has to do unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of global GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female participation in the labor force and lower income disparities, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring a growing net benefit – rising to an annual 1.5% of GDP.
This is due to the differing effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On one hand, higher CO2 emissions were a boon for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect at 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand by more than it increases cooling demand, resulting in a benefit of around 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, costing about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, resulting in a loss of approximately 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs, justifying cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the evaluation list also shows that the world's biggest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, putting things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This amounts to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs equated to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved worldwide to a significant extent.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy hardly changed.
The gain since 1900 cannot be overstated: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The biggest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio in 1970.
In 2000, it was 85%, which led to the rescue of three million lives annually – more than had been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents to thank for.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised an additional 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, the cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
Economically speaking, the costs of worse health at the beginning of the 20th century amounted to surprising 32% of global GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even though the optimists are not correct in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places much more), the overall picture is clear.
The majority of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available to address them, global problems have dramatically declined.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has significantly improved.
Furthermore, the evaluation list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not align our vision of the future with the most frightening stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather with objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
